ABOUT THE CODE:
●	I firstly selected the frames on which I have applied the algorithm, the function “frame_generator” does this work. The starting frame is frame 900 and ending frame is 1500.

●	In each frame, I applied gaussian transformation to smoothen the pixel intensity distribution and reduce noise. The function “gaussian_weights” does this.

●	The algorithm uses Pyramids to tackle fast moving objects, since lucas kanade alone can not effectively track fast moving objects. By progressively downsampling the image (build_pyramid function), large pixel jumps in the original video become tiny, mathematically manageable shifts at the lowest resolution. The Pyramid depth is 3. 
.
●	Finally the “lk_single_level” function calculates the gradient for each frame by vectorisation.
 
●	To focus exclusively on moving subjects, the pipeline uses a MOG2 background subtractor to generate a foreground mask, which is refined by morphological operations. Feature detection is restricted to this active mask, completely ignoring static backgrounds. To replace lost or drifting points, new features are dynamically added every three frames up to a set memory limit.

●	For detecting the feature the algorithm used the Shi-Tomasi method, which distinguishes features on the basis of intensity gradient. There was a maximum limit to the number of features that are to be tracked, it was set to 200 features. 

CHALLENGES FACED AND SOLUTIONS:
●	I applied parameter tuning on certain variables such, Quality level(Shi-Tomasi function), Maximum features, NUM_LEVELS(Pyramid depth). These were the crucial parameters that were to be tuned.

●	In the start of the video initially the Shi-Tomasi was detecting various points on the wall(as the background had various intensity gradients). I used the MOG2 function to ignore the static background wall.
●	What the MOG2 function does is, it tracks the history of a detected feature, if the feature looks like its normal state then it is a background feature. Otherwise it is a foreground feature. More elaborately if the mean square divided by variance is less than a threshold value then it is a foreground feature. Since the walls have various positions of sharp gradient, ignoring background features is necessary. 



