I have implemented the Artificial potential field concept to navigate through an obstacle environment, the target created attractive vectors while the road boundaries and obstacles created repulsive vectors. 

BRIEF THEORY:
The Visual Potential Field method uses attractive and repulsive forces to drive the bot. The obstacles and road boundaries create repulsion vectors and the target creates attraction vectors. 





FOE(focus of expansion) is the point where all the flow vector converges when the camera moves forward. The algorithm uses FOE for the estimation of TTC(time to collision). We evaluate FOE by solving a linear equation for a patch of features.









TTC is the expected time in which the car/bot will hit the obstacle and is evaluated by taking the distance between FOE and obstacle.




Finally I have used Lucas Kanade with pyramidal implementation to track the points as the camera proceeds. The lucas kanade algorithm first evaluated the optical flow vectors, from which we evaluated FOE, and then we evaluated TTC.

