         FUNCTIONS:
●	         The get_camera_axis function given the coordinate and orientation of the camera. I have added an draw_road_boundary function that draws a red line around the road boundary, this was done for the verification of whether the car is estimating the boundaries correctly or not.

●	The get_strip_mask function looks for bright patches on the road and ignores them, these are likely the white strips on the road, since they cause a lot of noise, they are ignored in repulsion vector calculation.

●	I included compute_foe and compute_ttc functions for FOE and TTC calculation.

●	The repulsive_force function calculates the repulsive vector for the obstacles, it is a vector pointed from obstacle feature to the foe point. Rather than adding the repulsive force for each and every obstacle feature, the algorithm chooses the obstacle feature with minimum TTC and uses it for force calculation
.
●	The attractive_force function just takes the absolute distance between car position and target as the major motivation for calculating the attractive force.   
   
●	The road_force function applies the force according to road potential(F_world), additionally an F_image component with 30% weight is also added. If the car is heading at 20 degrees right but is currently at the centre of the road, then the F_world function will not create any repulsive force but here F_image will contribute in the repulsive force and hence giving an angular safety from road boundaries.



●	Ultimately we have the desired_heading function which adds all the components(attractive, repulsive and road force) and applies a final coordinate transform. compute_speed looks for the lateral speed.

FLOW IN MAIN FUNCTION:
●	The main loop extracts fresh features after every 20 frames, Shi-Tomasi is used for feature detection and then pyramidal lucas kanade is applied, after that evaluation of FOE and TTC is done.
●	The algorithm then chooses the obstacle with least TTC and considers its flow vector, also the road force and attractive force from the target is calculated. All these forces are added and a final coordinate transform leads to desired speed and heading angle.

JUSTIFICATION FOR NON-CONVENTIONAL IMPLEMENTATIONS:

SINGLE-OBSTACLE-REPULSION:
●	Ideally the algorithm should add repulsion vectors for each obstacle detected, but due to poor obstacle detection there are a lot of obstacles that are creating noise. Hence I only choose the obstacle with the least TTC for repulsive force calculation. This idea worked to some extent and reduced the noise.

ANGULAR COMPONENT OF ROAD FORCE
●	The usual road force which is dependent just on the Euclidean distance of bot from the road boundary is not sufficient alone, when the car is at centre but at an non zero angle form the lateral axis(X-axis) then also it should have an repulsion from the road. The F_image variable with 30% weight takes care of it.

BRIGHT STRIP EXCLUSION:
●	Since the white strips on the road were causing a lot of noise by creating a false repulsion vector, I have ignored them for optical flow vector estimation. If there are bright pixels within a patch of 60 pixels, then ignore them because they are most likely road strips. This implementation also enhanced the performance.

EXTRA URGENCY FACTOR FOR OBSTACLES:
●	As I already mentioned that obstacle detection was not effective, so I added an extra urgency factor for the obstacles (urgency = 1/TTC). Now the obstacle force is proportional to 1/TTC^2 , this will increase the response towards nearer obstacles. Apart from this I also added a smoothing window of 5 frames, this basically takes average of forces among 5 frames, this was done for decreasing the noise. Both these implementations helped in reducing the noise.






